title: For Sale:  Colt's MK IV Series 70 Government Model .45 Automatic Caliber
postcontent:
This beautiful firearm was a present to myself in 1976, after graduating from the university and starting my new career. This 39-year-old Colt's MK IV Series 70 Government Model .45 Automatic Caliber pistol,  manufactured in 1976, during Colt’s glory days, is head and shoulders superior to the many Colts manufactured in the decades that followed, which saw the company struggle to survive a prolonged labor strike and being sold and resold, all, which resulted in much deteriorated quality control.

Being a true Colt factory nickel plated firearm, this pistol was finely polished and accurized prior to nickel plating and has always fired very dependably, smoothly and accurately. This weapon is a pleasure to shoot and to own.

I purchased this gun, new, for self-defense and for collecting. I have had it for 39 years. It has only been used for slight practice/target shooting. It works flawlessly and is in excellent condition. The custom grips provide a hand-filling excellent hold.

Please contact me for the link to a video that I've created including many more pictures of this great gun. REDACTED and REDACTED

I will ship anywhere in the USA, through an FFL Dealer, via USPS. The buyer will pay the actual shipping cost. I will honor the buyer's wishes as to how quickly he wants the gun delivered. The firearm must be shipped via a registered, insured, way, which provides maximum security and tracking. I will pay the fee that my FFL dealer charges me to send the gun to the buyer and the buyer will pay whatever fee his FFL dealer charges him to receive the firearm for him.

Please note: I only accept payment via USPS Money Orders and ship via USPS.

This is my first time selling a firearm online but I have sold a lot of things on eBay, where I am a highly regarded seller, having sold cars, motorcycles, vintage guitars and guitar amplifiers, and a wide variety of great things, all which have been in mint or near mint condition. Please check out my eBay seller's feedback - my eBay member ID is: 1sagestar8 - and buy with confidence here.

title: For Sale:  Glock 42 or 43 N82 Tactical IWB Holster
postcontent:
IWB holster for all handguns - subcompact, micro compact, compact, full size, J-frame revolvers. Please contact me with the make and model of your handgun and we will select the right holster to fit your handgun. 

N82 Tactical Story:

The Original Nate Squared Tactical Holster was developed to allow an individual to carry concealed all day comfortably. We had always thought that carrying a concealed firearm was just supposed to be comforting, not comfortable. After personally carrying some of the most popular IWB's on the market, we understood why so many people felt the same way. After collecting the proverbial box of holsters, we decided enough was enough and started working on our own holster design. We introduced our Original holster in October of 2009 and since then, thousands of people (some skeptically at first) have enjoyed the opportunity to not only be comforted by carrying a concealed firearm, but learned that you could truly carry all day comfortably. With Nate Squared Tactical, comfort is a reality, NOT JUST A SLOGAN.

COMFORT
Comfort was our biggest motivation in the design of our unique holsters. Each Series of Nate Squared Tactical holsters are made from quality oil-tanned leather, neoprene, and suede leather. Each holster is hand crafted to ensure the highest quality possible. We firmly stand behind the quality & craftsmanship of every holster we build.

- The oil-tanned leather will provide a durable, yet safe contact for the handgun.
- The soft suede backing allows your skin to breathe, so even when you sweat against the holster, it will still feel cool.
- The natural friction coefficient of suede displaces a percentage of the weight of your firearm. This allows you to carry the firearm without it's total weight pulling down against your waistband. It is the suede that allows us to utilize a design with a single clip.
- Neoprene is sandwiched between the oil-tanned leather and the suede leather. The neoprene provides the padding to protect you from the various edges of the firearm (slide, rear sight, hammer, beavertail, etc.) even when sitting in a vehicle, but also protects your investment. title: For Sale:  Saginaw SG M1 30 cal Carbine
postcontent:
Saginaw S.G. M1
30 Cal. Carbine 
Made in Grand Rapids in 1943
1st Block Serial numbers
Very good Condition
Has flash suppressor and extra clips 
Serial Number:3432499
Units produced 293,592

These were issued during world war II.  Here is information about M1's from wikipedia: Despite being designed by Winchester, the great majority of these guns were made by other companies (see list of Military contractors below). The largest producer was the Inland division of General Motors, but many others were made by contractors as diverse as IBM, the Underwood typewriter company, and the Rock-Ola jukebox company. Few contractors made all the parts for carbines bearing their names: some makers bought parts from other major contractors or sub-contracted minor parts to companies like Marlin Firearms or Auto-Ordnance. Parts by all makers were required to be interchangeable."

"When receivers were shipped for this purpose the manufacturers would often mark them for both companies." After doing some digging I found that M 1s with IG markings mean it was made by IBM and General Motors. Although Ive also read that the Saginaw with the SG marking stood for Grand Rapids. 

Links to what I'm referring to 
Wiki: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M1_carbine#Production
Forum: http://m1family.com/topic23.html 

If interested, or need additional information call Rick at REDACTED. Texts will not be answered.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Be reasonable
postcontent:
Guns are like cars people. When you drive them off the lot or carry them out of the store, they lose value. And yes, they both have blue books - buy one. I hate that you paid tax, but you're not going to get your tax and TICS $ back out of the firearm. 

Your Glock is not worth more than $450-500. I don't care what you've done to it or if it's solid gold or if Clint-F'ING-Eastwood rubbed his manhood on it. It doesn't add any value. None. 

Your Frankenstein-build 5.56 *might* be worth the sum of its parts. Not your time in building it as most of us can do it as well. Please stop listing them for $1,200+. Part the gun out. 

I WANT TO BUY reasonably priced used guns. Please check blue book or gunbroker for COMPLETED auctions to see what people are PAYING for your used merchandise. 

Thank you.
